<TrainingDetailsVTwo ID="x18266" Name="Cells" Layout="default-training_v2.xsl"><Title type="string" label="Title" readonly="false" hidden="false" required="true">Cells</Title><Abstract type="string" label="Abstract" readonly="false" hidden="false" required="true">A full-width banner image that rotates between all included images.</Abstract><IsTrainingHomePage type="boolean" label="Is this the training homepage?" readonly="false" hidden="false" required="false">false</IsTrainingHomePage><TrainingImage type="imagefile" label="Page Type Image" hidden="false" readonly="false" required="false"></TrainingImage><BodyCopy type="dhtml" label="Body Copy" readonly="false" hidden="false" required="false"><![CDATA[<strong></strong> A special layout process patterned after tables.<br />
<h4>Proper Use</h4>
These cells are meant for a limited number of major areas, services, or features of your office. The cells should not hold much content. Think of these are doorways to other pages.<br /><ol>
<li>Define how many cells ("doorways") that you need. For the sake of instruction, let's say seven (while seven major services or topics are feasible, more than four is less effective for users).</li>
<li>Decide how many cells per row. A row can only hold up to five cells, and that's crowded! We'll choose three per row.</li>
<li>Add seven cells to the Cell List</li>
<li>Create (or select existing) Cell Components and pick them in the order they should appear, left to right.</li>
</ol>Please note that you can change the number of cells on a row at will.  The page dynamically creates rows as needed to accommodate all the cells that you define.<br />
